Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It is comic with what schoolwork Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest, repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he considered the most stupid.
When he finally swallowed out his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he described it through a copier from Bush’s Iraqi script three years ago.
Not only did he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he did not hesitate to even use the title of the January 2007 Bush Statement as the title of his own declaration: "A New Way Forward."
Three years ago, he criticized Bush’s idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to Iraq, plagued by the civil war, as a “irresponsible and in its consequences catastrophic decision.”
But the months that followed showed that Bush’s strategy based on recommendations from field commanders was the only one that was possible and so successful that there is no mention of Iraq in the news reports today.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, but objectively left his successor with a much more grateful starting position than could be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will happen again.
The increase of the military contingent was again requested by field commanders, notably the chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who, despite his subordinate practices, even harshly criticized the hesitant shooters in the White House.
He asked for 40,000 men to break the situation to the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he did not find anything better, and so at least deceived the general with 10 thousand soldiers.
From Europe, he was able to sweep out the promise of another 5 thousand, although he himself initially counted at least 10 thousand.
The most problematic of Obama’s strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to end this process in three years.
Many have doubts that the half-increase will yield the same fruits as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the brotherly wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well-organized, its leaders honour agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is characterized by the opposite symptom - no one can be trusted and no agreements are observed.
Badly prepared in these circumstances, the Afghan security forces are used to changing masters every day as they like.
Political institutions, even if they are formally established, will remain only a village behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extremely difficult given the vague situation, which further complicates Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the construction of a “accessible state”, which is the minimalist goal of the entire operation, does not seem too realistic.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is striking with its voluntarism.
In the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the verge of an explosion.
To believe that the soldiers sent to the war wreck for the purpose of "short return home" will cause the miracle done here, can only the soul truly romantic, untouched by reality.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will perceive it as an indirect acknowledgment of the American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is down to minus.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the Hindu Mountains.
Another factor capable of radically affecting the situation is the developments around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the heightened sanctions on Iran fail, the U.S. will face the overwhelming question of whether to try to solve the problem by military force.
It will need to be answered at a time when, according to Obama, America will step towards a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
Any such solution, however, will also mean a dramatic turn in the Afghan situation.
The only patch for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years to the presidential election, and therefore there is still enough time to come up with another strategy if it turns out to be a total downfall.
