Czech Discovery: A Substance That Takes Into 'HIV' Viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists are testing new compounds that can slow the spread of the HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the enhanced substance is that it also occupies viruses that have already gained immunity against drugs.
This fact in some cases overrides the fact that the compound on the common variant of the virus does not act as strongly as some already available medicines.
AIDS cannot be cured.
However, a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body can significantly extend the life of patients.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of the multiplication of the virus has also resulted in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are already ineffective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Czech Academy of Sciences, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with the virus resistance.
They have shown that substances called metallocarbonates act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalcarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all the drugs used today, and therefore can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new ‘improved’ compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
Metal carbonates have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages made up of bore, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Strange and Resilient Virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV protease-induced splitting of the HIV virus, mature infectious viral particles would not be produced.
When we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, researchers describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is further systematically modified.
A little weaker but more reliable.
The effect of this series of anti-HIV protease substances has been tested in the tube and also against its resistant (resistant) variants obtained from patients infected with the HIV virus.
The effect of metalocarbonates on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as that of clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which drugs are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and also their other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical modifications make metalcarborans interesting compounds for further research towards the design of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína Rezáčová, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
