The United Nations Group has drafted a plan to reduce emissions.
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized by far-reaching unconditional positions and mutual support -- focused again on Friday to release a document proposing an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gas emissions over the next 40 years with industrialized nations bearing most of the burden in the near term.
The text, which may provide the starting point for a final political agreement on greenhouse gas regulation, highlights the remaining obstacles as well as lights up the way forward.
But important progress has been seen in the talks that took place at the wrong time with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Created by the UN Ad hoc Working Group, this text unobtrusively states how much money wealthy countries should provide to the poor to cope with global warming in the short and long term.
And it provides a whole range of choices for key issues, including how to develop and manage emerging economies to limit their carbon output and what should be the upper limit of global warming that politicians will still be able to tolerate.
This gives the process a great deal of flexibility, says John Coequyt, chief executive of the Washington Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, tailored the 180-page text from the meeting to focus on what high-ranking UN climate official Yvo de Boer described as “the big picture.”
It overshadows the outlines for a possible agreement in which the industrialized nations could jointly limit their emissions to 25 to 45 percent by the year compared to 1990 levels, while the major developing countries could reduce their emissions to 15 to 30 percent during that period.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions by 2050 between 50 and 95 percent.
The European Union promised to provide $3.6 trillion over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to climate change – from managing floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Still on Friday, however, the same kind of verbal fireworks prevailed in last week’s talks.
U.S. Special Envoy for Climate Change Todd Stern has rejected a speech calling for mandatory greenhouse gas emissions reductions for industrialized countries compared to voluntary reductions for major emerging economies if they weren’t funded by the developed world.
The shift signaled that the Obama administration had set a tougher line towards China just two years ago.
The United States will not join the treaty without transferring major developing countries and implementing action, Stern said, who also complained that the text was not sufficient to secure restrictions and should be checked by external observers.
Stern made this comment an hour after Chinese Deputy Secretary of State He Yafei told the U.S. chief climate negotiator that either a lack of "peasant reason" or "extreme irresponsibility" led earlier this week to the announcement that the United States would not help China financially to cope with global warming.
With the future of the economic path of the major world powers at stake, gaps have broken up both within the developing world and between the industrialized world and emerging economies.
The current struggle is mostly about the preservation of individual economies rather than the preservation of the planet, between China and the United States regarding the fulfillment of their respective commitments, while poorer nations point out that two dozen of the world’s most influential countries ignore the scientific imperative to take more decisive action.
Ricardo Ulate, Costa Rica’s delegate, said it’s not surprising that major powers are fighting for who should bear the cost of limiting greenhouse gases, while vulnerable countries have become much more aggressive in finding ways to prevent large emitters from responsible in their actions.
It’s clearly a game about a new economic hegemony developing, Ulate said, who also serves as a regional adviser on regional climate change in Mexico and Central America for international nature conservation.
Some of the countries that are most vulnerable to the impacts of climate change have indicated that they would like to continue to enforce the legally binding agreement in Copenhagen, but most of the key participants said the best outcome of the talks would be a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, produced a 24-page draft agreement last Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who led international climate talks for the benefit of the European Commission, said the push by small island nations “has caused a political blow to the entire polyrytic process” in part because they are now united and demand action from growing economies such as China and India.
The negotiations sparked a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the remaining controversial issues before the heads of government struggled to reach an agreement.
High-ranking officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Rameš and Chinese deputy minister, came out of the planes and walked through the Bella Center halls to the closed doors of meetings and new conferences so they could set out claims to be considered next week.
The enormous scale of the assembly—when 13,000 people moved daily from and to the congress centre, guitar-playing activists staged ironic shows at night about the countries they thought they had sent them, and proposals were hand-to-hand transmitted on paper rather than by e-mail—controlled by call.
Intensity is only a surge: almost all key ministers were present in Copenhagen and, earlier, in the middle of 60 heads of state.
We got into the high categories, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, the deputy minister for global policy at international nature conservation.
Heavy weights are coming.
