He hopes the new service will eventually connect Britain with an international network of fast, reliable trains and connect large agglomerations of Midland, the North and Scotland with London.
The overlooked stagnant waters should shorten traffic times in passenger transport and on business journeys, and switching from aircraft and cars to rail could reduce carbon emissions and eliminate congestion on roads.
Theoretically, three major political parties have won for this vision.
But the tens of billions of pounds needed to build a new national rail network, the inevitable struggle for projects and concerns about environmental disruption have now slowed the construction of British high-speed lines.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company created in January to provide the government with a feasible study, passed its report to Lord Adonis on December 30, the Times.
It provided him with a detailed map of the route for the next planned stage of the high-speed network.
The new route between London and West Midland has been designed to be within five meters in urban areas and neighborhoods where the impact on living spaces could be problematic.
In the open landscape, the final route was planned for 25 meters.
HS2 also plans to identify three options for a large-scale high-speed network leading north.
Lord Adonis will answer in the spring.
The preferred option is a Y-shaped configuration, where one high-speed track should lead to Western Midland.
The track should be divided near Birmingham with one branch, passing from Pennines to Manchester and Scotland, and the other, leading northeast to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
One route leads to Scotland.
"It seems that the most powerful choice has been made," said a railway expert.
Once completed, the driving time between London and Edinburgh will be shortened to two hours and 40 minutes.
The first phase, which will not be opened before 2025, could allow passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes compared to more than an hour in the present.
The proposals would allow trains to travel at a speed of 2,250 miles per hour, making the UK network the fastest in Europe.
The initial track is already being designed to take on 400m long trains capable of carrying 1,100 passengers.
Up to 18 sets could operate every hour on the London-Birmingham route.
This means that the London terminal would be able to serve up to 20,000 passengers per hour if needed.
Given capital constraints, the existing station is expected to be expanded to cover the high-speed network.
Experts from the railway industry say that only San Pancras International or Euston offer such potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he intends to implement this scheme, but extensive public consultations and planning procedures mean that no final decision will be made before the general elections.
Even if it puts the wheels in motion, the network should be built in parts.
