In his speech in Oslo, “Justice War,” Obama earned praise from the right.
The American right on Friday welcomed a speech that Barack Obama delivered a day earlier in Oslo, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize winner defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
Conservatives, who first mocked Obama’s award on October 9, this time applauded the presidential speech, including Sarah Palin, a former vice president candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, Palin, a muse of the right-wing Republican wing, told USA Today, adding that she herself expressed herself on the topic of the "sometimes necessary" war in her memoirs that are just coming out.
War is, of course, the last thing Americans would want to have to do, but it is necessary.
All terrorists should be detained there, he believes.
President Obama, who inherited two wars in Afghanistan and Iraq from his predecessor, George W. Bush, on Thursday in Oslo justified the deployment of forces and used the speech to clarify his decision to send an additional 30,000 troops to Afghanistan nine days before.
Another Obama opponent, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done “very good work” in Oslo.
I think the speech was really very good, congratulated the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who especially appreciated the president's mention of "the existence of evil in the world".
In a way, I considered this speech quite historic," Gingrich said during an interview on the radio show "The Takeaway".
