75% of working mothers have work-related problems.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who intend to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and Working Careers of Spanish Women' conducted by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The study involved 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 and the results are unambiguous: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities on the labour market due to motherhood.
The study highlights that at the beginning of a partnership there are many differences in opinions about the number of children depending on whether they work or not, and also according to the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside of home, work part-time or do not have a stable job begin to live with their partner earlier, give birth to their first child earlier and generally have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, postpone partnership and maternity, and have fewer offspring.
“Women aged 35 to 49 with stable employment have their first child on average 3.7 years from the beginning of their partnership.This figure is 4.1 in the case of women who have devoted most of their lives to achieving their stable employment and have therefore had to postpone their partnership and the arrival of children.
The type of profession also has a strong influence on maternity, although it has a smaller influence on the time of starting a life with a partner,” explains Margarita Delgado, a researcher at CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage and the birth of a offspring is the degree of education.
The higher the level of education, the higher the age when women get married and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group 35 to 49, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at 25.1 and 32.1.
"There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with primary education marry and give birth to their first child before they can find a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education prefer to get a stable job before marrying and giving birth to their first child.”
