The manual brake system is now mandatory.
As with the ABS anti-blocking system, the ESP stability control and manual brake assistance systems will become mandatory for European cars.
In fact, it already forms part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest, the deadline is February 2011.
The measures introduced in the EU aim to improve the protection of pedestrians, while working in a way that can help prevent many collisions.
The manual brake assistance system increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which is detected by the system after the driver steps down.
But it’s not always possible to keep this pressure up to the end.
According to a study conducted by automotive parts manufacturer Bosch, one-third of drivers who have an accident did not squeeze the brake before a collision, and half of them did not use the brake power to the fullest.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires the maximum from the braking system, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study conducted in the EU alone, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1,100 pedestrian-related fatalities could be avoided annually.
The reduction of this number will be even more pronounced – according to calculations one in four accidents affecting people would be avoided – after the introduction of so-called smart manual braking systems.
In this case, vehicles will be equipped with a system that (using radar or camera) captures obstacles and reports them to the driver, in addition to light braking.
If the driver reacts, it will help him increase the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond, even if the collision cannot be avoided, the device will impact the brake as intensely as possible and reduce the risk of damage to a minimum.
